title.narrative: ADOLESCENTS HEALTHY DEVELOP. & SERVICES

description.narrative: By 2021, adolescents, especially the most disadvantaged, have increased knowledge of healthy development and available services., which contributes to Cross-Sectoral Adolescent Development, Evaluation, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women (Covid), Research. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2021, all adolescents, especially the disadvantaged, increasingly practice key behaviours for healthy development and participate in decision-making at all levels to accelerate the realisation of their rights.

title.narrative: By 2021, adolescents, especially the most disadvantaged, have increased knowledge of healthy development and available services.

description.narrative: 18,730,447;adolescents, parents and caregivers were reached with information about mental health services, tips and tools through UNICEF’s “Every Day is Mind Day” campaign, Facebook live events, and infographics. 1,304,423 users accessed comprehensive sexual and reproductive health (SRH) and mental health information through the LoveCareStation, while online counselling was provided to 10,232 youth. 1,541 vulnerable adolescents gained soft and vocational skills to secure productive work, make informed decisions about their health and positively engage in their communities. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:01/02/2022
